  volume    =  79,
  number    =  17,
  pages     = "4539--4550",
  abstract  = "Identifying robust biomarkers of drug response constitutes a key
               challenge in precision medicine. Patient-derived tumor xenografts
               (PDX) have emerged as reliable preclinical models that more
               accurately recapitulate tumor response to chemo- and targeted
               therapies. However, the lack of computational tools makes it
               difficult to analyze high-throughput molecular and pharmacologic
               profiles of PDX. We have developed Xenograft Visualization \&
               Analysis (Xeva), an open-source software package for in vivo
               pharmacogenomic datasets that allows for quantification of
               variability in gene expression and pathway activity across PDX
               passages. We found that only a few genes and pathways exhibited
               passage-specific alterations and were therefore not suitable for
               biomarker discovery. Using the largest PDX pharmacogenomic
